  <sec sec-type="intro" id="SEC1">
    <title>Introduction</title>
    <p>Metabolomics is defined as the science of qualitative and quantitative measurement of small molecule metabolites in living systems. The metabolome of a cell, a tissue, or an organism refers to the collection of all small molecule metabolites present in that biological system (<xref rid="B1" ref-type="bibr">1</xref>,<xref rid="B2" ref-type="bibr">2</xref>). Plants are unique in that they have developed their complex secondary metabolism through more than 900 million years of evolution. The astounding chemical diversity and metabolic complexity in plants are highlighted by estimates suggesting that metabolites in green plants number in the millions (<xref rid="B3" ref-type="bibr">3</xref>). These metabolites play crucial roles in various aspects of plant biology, including growth, development, and responses to environmental challenges (<xref rid="B3" ref-type="bibr">3</xref>,<xref rid="B4" ref-type="bibr">4</xref>). Plant metabolites contribute to the intricate web of biochemical reactions and signaling pathways that orchestrate plant physiology. In this context, the emerging field of plant metabolomics has garnered substantial attention, offering new opportunities to uncover the intricate metabolic networks in plants.</p>
    <p>In recent decades, the study of plant metabolism has undergone significant advancements, largely driven by the emergence of metabolomics. Due to the enormous diversity and structural complexity of small molecule metabolites across plant species, their identification and functional analysis pose a significant challenge to researchers (<xref rid="B5" ref-type="bibr">5</xref>). The advance of metabolomics analytical technology, for example high-resolution mass spectrometry (HRMS) coupled with ultra-performance liquid chromatography (UPLC) separation, makes genome-scale metabolomic analysis possible, enabling detection of metabolites at an unparalleled sensitivity, resolution, accuracy, and throughput (<xref rid="B3" ref-type="bibr">3</xref>,<xref rid="B4" ref-type="bibr">4</xref>,<xref rid="B6" ref-type="bibr">6</xref>,<xref rid="B7" ref-type="bibr">7</xref>). Metabolomic technology based on high-performance of liquid chromatography combining high-resolution mass spectrometry is suitable for detecting the broad range of liquid-soluble metabolites found in plants, thus has become an standard approach for plant metabolomics research.</p>
    <p>Many databases and supporting tools related to metabolomics research and data sharing have been launched in the last two decades. Examples include MassBank (<xref rid="B8" ref-type="bibr">8</xref>), MassBase (<xref rid="B9" ref-type="bibr">9</xref>), HMDB (<xref rid="B10" ref-type="bibr">10</xref>), MetaboLights (<xref rid="B11" ref-type="bibr">11</xref>), Metabolomics Workbench (<xref rid="B12" ref-type="bibr">12</xref>), XMRs (<xref rid="B13" ref-type="bibr">13</xref>), RIKEN MetaDatabase (<xref rid="B14" ref-type="bibr">14</xref>), Metlin(<xref rid="B15" ref-type="bibr">15</xref>) and BinBase (<xref rid="B16" ref-type="bibr">16</xref>). While these resources provide many general tools for metabolomics data sharing and analysis, annotation with compound standard mass spectra, and profiling of MS-based metabolic data, they are not completely satisfactory when facing the many of the specific challenges of plant metabolomics research. One factor is that the rapid advance of MS technologies made many of the spectral repository data obsolete due to lower mass spectral qualities, i.e. accuracy, resolution, and sensitivity. Particularly, the shortcomings of the instruments and experimental conditions used to produce much of the existing MS data has resulted in limited coverage of metabolite peaks, reduced mass spectral quality, and lower analytical power. Furthermore, for plant metabolomics research, the lack of both reference metabolome and high-quality spectral data for standard compounds, as well as high-throughput analytical tools, has become a major bottleneck for the discovery and functional study of phytochemicals in plants.</p>
    <p>To meet the needs of front-running phytochemical research, we have undertaken to address several challenges faced by plant metabolomics research: (i) We have generated untargeted mass spectral data, leveraging the most advanced LC–MS platform (UPLC-Q-Orbitrap-MS), from &gt;150 plant species collected across five major phyla: Bryophyta, Lycopodiopsida, Pteridophyta, Gymnospermae and Angiospermae. (ii) We built a ‘Reference Metabolome Database for Plants’ (abbreviated as RefMetaPlant), using a computation protocol we developed for constructing a reference metabolome. Inspired by the reference genome concept, the reference plant metabolome was constructed by collecting and ‘assembling’ its metabolites’ mass spectral data (MS1/MS2) from all available organs/tissues of the species. The first release of RefMetaPlant contains the reference metabolome for &gt;150 plants, and has functions for metabolic research that were aimed to parallel that of RefSeq (<xref rid="B17" ref-type="bibr">17</xref>) for genomic studies. (iii) We have integrated standard compound mass spectral libraries for annotation, including both experimental reference mass spectra and <italic toggle="yes">in silico</italic> mass spectra, and developed a set of related query and analytical tools like ‘LC–MS/MS Query’, ‘RefMetaBlast’ and ‘CompoundLibBlast’ for plants metabolome searches and profiling, and metabolite identification.</p>
    <p>It is worth noting that many existing metabolic databases predominantly focus on model organisms and a small number of plant species (<xref rid="B18" ref-type="bibr">18–21</xref>), which poses significant limitations that hinder the exploration of the metabolomics space in the broad field of plant research. Therefore, we have established RefMetaPlant as a broader more integrated platform to enable increased interactions between scientists from different parts of the world and ease the flow of information within the scientific community (<xref rid="B22" ref-type="bibr">22</xref>). RefMetaPlant serves as an integrated database and analysis platform dedicated to becoming the centralized resource for plant metabolomic research. It aims to standardize and integrate reference metabolome data, providing a comprehensive platform for researchers in plant metabolomics, genetics, and related fields. RefMetaPlant is freely available at <ext-link xlink:href="https://www.biosino.org/RefMetaDB/" ext-link-type="uri">https://www.biosino.org/RefMetaDB/</ext-link>, which offers a user-friendly web interface and a variety of easy-to-use tools for the functions mentioned above. This comprehensive platform caters to a broad audience, including scientists in plant metabolomics research, geneticists in plant breeding, and even consumers interested in understanding the chemical contents of plants. RefMetaPlant was established to accelerate advancements in plant metabolomics research, foster collaborations and promote a deeper understanding of plant metabolism.</p>
  </sec>
  <sec sec-type="materials|methods" id="SEC2">
    <title>Materials and methods</title>
    <sec id="SEC2-1">
      <title>Plant materials</title>
      <p>To broadly cover terrestrial plants, we collected plant samples from various sources (<xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary Table S1</xref>). A total of 153 plant species have been collected so far, with each species comprising one or more tissues, like leaf, flower, seed, stem or root. Three biological replicated samples were obtained for each tissue. The collected samples were immediately frozen in liquid nitrogen before stored at −80°C. For study cases 1 and 2, rice and maize samples were harvested in Jiangsu (Yangzhou, southeastern China) and in Hainan (Sanya, southern China), respectively.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-2">
      <title>DNA extraction, PCR amplification, ITS sequencing and annotation</title>
      <p>Fresh leaf tissue was first ground into powder with liquid nitrogen. Total genomic DNA was subsequently extracted using the Plant Genomic DNA Kit (Tiangen Biotech Co., China) according to the manufacturer's instructions. The plant internal transcribed spacer 2 (ITS2) region was amplified using the following primers: ITS2-2F (5′-ATGCGATACTTGGTGTGAAT-3′) and ITS2-3R (5′-GACGCTTCTCCAGACTACAAT-3′). PCR was performed in 50 μl reaction mixtures, containing 5 μl of 10× Buffer (including 2.5 mM Mg<sup>2+</sup>), 1 μl of Taq polymerase (TaKaRa), 1.5 μl of each PCR primer (10 μM), 1 μl of dNTP (10mM) and 1 μl of DNA extract (20ng/μl), and the total volume was adjusted to 50 μl with sterile deionized water. PCR amplification was conducted according to the following procedure: 95°C for 5 min, 35 cycles of 95°C for 30 s, 58°C for 30 s and 72°C for 1.5 min, and a final extension at 72°C for 7 min. PCR products were analyzed by electrophoresis in a 1% agarose gel. The PCR products were purified using an AxyPrep DNA Gel Extraction Kit (AXYGEN, Hangzhou, China) and sequenced bidirectionally using a ABI 3730XL sequencer (Applied Biosystems Co., USA) based on the Sanger sequencing method at Shanghai Personalbio Technology Co., Ltd. The sequenced ITS2 sequences were aligned against the NCBI NT database with the megablast tool (<xref rid="B23" ref-type="bibr">23</xref>), and the species with the highest sequence similarity was selected.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-3">
      <title>Metabolite extraction and mass spectral analysis</title>
      <p>The samples were processed for mass spectral analysis as described in our previous study (<xref rid="B24" ref-type="bibr">24</xref>). In brief, the freeze-dried tissues were ground using a tissue grinder (No. 05010997; Shanghai BiHeng Biotechnology Company Limited, Shanghai, China) for 2 min at 55 Hz. 150 mg of powder was weighed and mixed with 1.5 ml 70% aqueous methanol (containing 1 mg/l capsaicin as the internal standard). The samples were vortexed every 10 min three times and extracted overnight at 4°C. Following centrifugation at 12 000 g for 15 min, all the supernatants were filtered using a 0.22 μm filter and transferred to a liquid phase bottle for subsequent analysis.</p>
      <p>Samples were analyzed on a Waters Acquity Ultra Performance Liquid Chromatography system equipped with an ACQUITY UPLC BEH C18 column (1.7 μm, 2.1 mm × 100 mm) coupled with Q Exactive hybrid Q-Orbitrap-high resolution mass spectrometry (Q-Orbitrap-HRMS) (Thermo Fisher Scientific). The instrument parameter settings used for the analysis followed the procedure outlined in our previous study (<xref rid="B24" ref-type="bibr">24</xref>).</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-4">
      <title>Workflow for assembling the reference metabolome</title>
      <p>The workflow for constructing the plant reference metabolome consisted of four major steps (Figure <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">1B</xref>): (i) Raw MS data processing: Raw MS files were processed in Compound Discoverer software (version 3.2, Thermo Scientific) with automatic workflow for LC spectra alignment by retention time (RT) and peak detection. To refine the metabolite features, a set of criteria were applied (<xref rid="B25" ref-type="bibr">25</xref>), including reproducibility &lt;90%, sample to blank ratio &lt;10%, peak area less than 1E5, and elimination of features exhibiting multi-ion adducts (such as Na<sup>+</sup>, K<sup>+</sup>, NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup>, Cl<sup>−</sup>), isotopes, in-source fragmentation, or dimerization. (ii) Assembly of reference metabolome: an in-house script based on Xcalibur Development Kit (XDK) in Xcalibur software was first used to automatically acquire MS1/MS2 paired data from the raw LC−MS/MS files derived from distinct tissues of the plant species. The repetitive features identified from these diverse tissues were merged to establish the reference metabolome, encompassing spectral features separately in both ESI positive and negative ion mode. The merging process adhered to the following parameters: mass tolerance 5 ppm; retention time tolerance 0.2 min. (iii) Annotation of reference metabolome: the annotation of the reference metabolome was carried out following our prior research (<xref rid="B24" ref-type="bibr">24</xref>). In summary, we employed two complementary approaches for this process. Initially, we searched against the experimental reference mass spectra library obtained from public databases and structurally annotated MS2 spectra. Subsequently, we utilized predicted theoretical spectra to further enhance the scope of the structural annotations. To achieve a hierarchical chemical classification of the compounds, we utilized the Ruby application programming interface within the ClassyFire software (<xref rid="B26" ref-type="bibr">26</xref>) to generate the chemical classes. (iv) Creating reference metabolome files: sample, instrument, MS data and annotation information were integrated to generate reference metabolome file in .msr or .mgf format.</p>
      <fig position="float" id="F1">
        <label>Figure 1.</label>
        <caption>
          <p>Integration of plant species and metabolome data. (<bold>A</bold>) A taxonomic tree depicting the taxonomic relationships among 153 plant species that are representative of the five major phyla: Bryophyta (red), Lycopodiopsida (purple), Pteridophyte (yellow), Gymnospermae (green) and Angiospermae. The color scheme for subgroups of Angiospermae: ANA grade, grey; Magnoliids, orange; Monocotyledons, magenta; and Dicotyledons, blue. (<bold>B</bold>) Workflow for constructing plant reference metabolome, which consists of four major steps: (i) raw MS data processing; (ii) assembly of reference metabolome; (iii) annotation of reference metabolome and (iv) creating reference metabolome files (detailed description in Materials and methods). (<bold>C</bold>) Global metabolic profiles of the reference metabolome for 153 plants. The innermost circuit depicts the taxonomic relationships of the 153 species. Circuits A–H display the profiles of metabolites belonging to eight chemical classes (A = alkaloids, B = amino acid derivatives, C = flavonoids, D = lipids, E = nucleotides and derivatives, F = phenols, G = phenylpropanoids, H = terpenoids). The intensity of color shading in circuits A-H indicates the number of metabolites detected for each species. The bar chart in circuit I represents the total number of detected metabolites. (<bold>D</bold>) The reference metabolome for <italic toggle="yes">Callistemon rigidus</italic>. The header section of .msr file is illustrated to the left. Metabolites are represented as dots, with chemical classifications indicated by their color. Examples of annotated and unknown metabolites are presented at the top and bottom, respectively.</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="gkad980fig1" position="float"/>
      </fig>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-5">
      <title>Construction of standard compounds mass spectral libraries</title>
      <p>The standard compounds mass spectral libraries consist of experimental MS/MS spectra and <italic toggle="yes">in silico</italic> spectra. The experimental MS/MS spectra data were sourced from a range of databases including MassBank (<xref rid="B8" ref-type="bibr">8</xref>), MoNA (<ext-link xlink:href="https://mona.fiehnlab.ucdavis.edu/" ext-link-type="uri">https://mona.fiehnlab.ucdavis.edu/</ext-link>), ReSpect (<xref rid="B27" ref-type="bibr">27</xref>), FiehnLib (<xref rid="B28" ref-type="bibr">28</xref>) and RIKEN PlaSMA (<ext-link xlink:href="http://plasma.riken.jp/" ext-link-type="uri">http://plasma.riken.jp/</ext-link>). According to the use of specific keywords and meticulous filter criteria, the mass spectral data corresponding to the metabolites of interest under investigation were retrieved. For each individual metabolite, we procured its corresponding mass spectrum, molecular formula, molecular weight and potential metabolite information from these databases.</p>
      <p>The <italic toggle="yes">in silico</italic> mass spectral data were generated by converting the structural information of biologically relevant compounds into theoretical spectrograms using CFM-ID software (<xref rid="B29" ref-type="bibr">29</xref>). The structural data for each compound were collected from four biologically relevant structure databases: KEGG (<xref rid="B30" ref-type="bibr">30</xref>), KNApSAcK (<xref rid="B31" ref-type="bibr">31</xref>), PubChem (<xref rid="B32" ref-type="bibr">32</xref>) and UNPD (<xref rid="B33" ref-type="bibr">33</xref>). For the KEGG database, ‘2Dmol’ files obtained via the ‘python-Bio.KEGG’ API were utilized to fill in missing structural information through the application of OpenBabel software (<xref rid="B34" ref-type="bibr">34</xref>), as SMILES, InChIKey and InChI were not available. In the case of the PubChem database, compounds from the PubChem classification browser, annotated with NCBI BioSystems (<xref rid="B35" ref-type="bibr">35</xref>), biological role classification from ChEBI Ontology (<xref rid="B36" ref-type="bibr">36</xref>), and classifications as flavonoids or prenol lipids from LIPID MAPS structure database (<xref rid="B37" ref-type="bibr">37</xref>) were downloaded.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-6">
      <title>Implementation of structure query and spectral query</title>
      <p>The structure query was implemented via the function ‘Search metabolites’ using the ‘Structure Query’ tool. The JavaScript based molecule editor JSME (<xref rid="B38" ref-type="bibr">38</xref>) was employed to transform the drawn molecule structure into a canonical SMILES format. Subsequently, the SMILES representation of the query molecule was converted into an InChI string using the chemistry development kit (<xref rid="B39" ref-type="bibr">39</xref>). This InChI string was then utilized for a query against the plant reference metabolome to identify matching hits.</p>
      <p>For the spectra query, the function ‘Search metabolites’, particularly in the ‘LC–MS/MS Query’, as well as related functions such as RefMetaBlast and CompoundLibBlast analytical tools, the INCOS algorithm (<xref rid="B40" ref-type="bibr">40</xref>) was employed through java scripts to score the similarity between reference mass spectra. In brief, the reference mass spectra that have similar precursor m/z (within a user-defined precursor mass tolerance range) with query mass spectra were retrieved and compared for similarity using the INCOS algorithm. Reference mass spectra with a similarity score &gt;0.75 were used to assign annotation to query mass spectra.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-7">
      <title>Implementation of analytical tools ‘RefMetaBlast’ and ‘CompoundLibBlast’</title>
      <p>The RefMetaBlast and CompoundLibBlast analytical tools, which can be used via the function ‘Analyze Spectra’, are designed for LC–MS/MS data annotation. These tools are intended for use with high-resolution LC–MS/MS data acquired in centroid mode and provided in standard formats such as mzML, mzXML or mzData. Upon submission of an annotation task, the LC–MS data undergoes initial processing using a custom R script built upon the XCMS package (<xref rid="B41" ref-type="bibr">41</xref>). This processing encompasses peak detection, peak filtering, and extraction of MS2 spectra. Subsequently, each MS2 spectrum is annotated by a database search via the INCOS algorithm. The RefMetaBlast tool can be used to analyze a sample's spectra with a reference metabolome from a specific species. The CompoundLibBlast tool analyzes a sample's spectra with public mass spectral data and <italic toggle="yes">in silico</italic> mass spectral data. In addition, the result of matched or annotated metabolites can be conveniently downloaded in both JSON and CSV formats.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-8">
      <title>Database and web interface implementation</title>
      <p>The RefMetaPlant project was developed and integrated on the Java SSM framework (Spring, Spring MVC and MyBatis) and the packaged application was deployed on an Apache Tomcat web server (<ext-link xlink:href="http://tomcat.apache.org/" ext-link-type="uri">http://tomcat.apache.org/</ext-link>) which runs on the CentOS 6.8 system. The interactive RefMetaPlant web interface was developed using Bootstrap (3.3.7, <ext-link xlink:href="http://getbootstrap.com/" ext-link-type="uri">http://getbootstrap.com/</ext-link>) and jQuery (2.1.0, <ext-link xlink:href="http://jquery.com/" ext-link-type="uri">http://jquery.com/</ext-link>) and implemented in JSP. All the data in RefMetaPlant were stored in a relational database MySQL (5.1.73, <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.mysql.com/" ext-link-type="uri">http://www.mysql.com/</ext-link>). The 2D and 3D structure of compounds were displayed using Smiles Drawer and JSmol (<ext-link xlink:href="http://wiki.jmol.org/index.php/JSmol" ext-link-type="uri">http://wiki.jmol.org/index.php/JSmol</ext-link>), respectively. The JavaScript plotting library Flot (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.flotcharts.org/" ext-link-type="uri">http://www.flotcharts.org/</ext-link>) was used to draw interactive mass spectrum. The interactive result tables for annotated metabolites were generated using DataTables (<ext-link xlink:href="https://www.datatables.net/" ext-link-type="uri">https://www.datatables.net/</ext-link>). The back-end logic processing and data analysis were mainly implemented through R and Java scripts. The database is available online without registration and is optimized for Chrome, Opera, Firefox, Windows Edge and macOS Safari.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-9">
      <title>Statistical analysis</title>
      <p>Statistical analyses were mainly conducted using R software (<ext-link xlink:href="https://www.R-project.org/" ext-link-type="uri">https://www.R-project.org/</ext-link>). Affinity Propagation (AP) clustering was employed to group metabolites with similar abundance profiles utilizing the ‘apcluster’ package in R (<xref rid="B42" ref-type="bibr">42</xref>). The taxonomic relationships among species were generated from the NCBI Taxonomy database (<xref rid="B43" ref-type="bibr">43</xref>), and visualized using the interactive Tree of Life (iTOL) web server (<xref rid="B44" ref-type="bibr">44</xref>). Other data analyses were carried out by in-house scripts written in R or Perl. The manuscript figures were mostly drawn by R.</p>
    </sec>
  </sec>
  <sec sec-type="results" id="SEC3">
    <title>Results</title>
    <sec id="SEC3-1">
      <title>Constructing a reference metabolome for plants</title>
      <p>A reference metabolome refers to the global collection of all metabolites for a given species. An analog comparison between the reference metabolome and metabolites for a given species mirrors that between the genome and genes for the species. In this study, the reference metabolome for a plant species is constructed by collecting and ‘assembling’ its metabolites’ mass spectral data (MS1/MS2) from all available organs/tissues of the species. Nowadays the high-resolution mass spectrometry can detect and identify a massive number of heterogeneous phytochemicals that have highly diverse structures and chemical and physical properties, usually numbering in the tens of thousands. Thus, in order to construct a plant reference metabolome an efficient computing process must be implemented to handle and resolve the mass spectral data, to eliminate redundant features, and to annotate detected metabolites.</p>
      <p>To broadly cover terrestrial plants, we have so far collected tissue samples from more than 150 plant species that are representative of the five major phyla: Bryophyta, Lycopodiopsida, Pteridophyte, Gymnospermae, and Angiospermae (Figure <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">1A</xref>, and <xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary Table S1</xref>). Their classifications were validated by ITS sequencing on each plant sample (<xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary Table S2</xref>).</p>
      <p>Mass spectral analysis was performed using ultra-performance liquid chromatography-tandem mass spectrometry (UPLC–MS/MS) platform on the tissues collected for each plant species. The raw spectral data were processed and filtered to obtain high-quality feature signals (Figure <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">1B</xref>). To assemble the reference metabolome for each plant species, MS1/MS2 spectra acquired from different tissue samples were merged for ESI positive and negative ion modes, by removing duplicated features. Then unique spectral features were annotated using compound spectral libraries before reference metabolome files (in .msr or .mgf format) were created for each species (Figure <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">1B</xref>).</p>
      <p>The first release of the reference metabolome illustrates the metabolic diversity and complexity of each of the 153 plant species (Figure <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">1C</xref>, and <xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary Table S3</xref>). Notably, annotated metabolites are classified into eight groups, i.e. alkaloids, amino acid derivatives, flavonoids, lipids, nucleotides and derivatives, phenols, phenylpropanoids, and terpenoids. As an example, the reference metabolome of <italic toggle="yes">Callistemon rigidus</italic> is depicted in Figure <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">1D</xref>. It contains MS1/MS2 data for all metabolites detected in <italic toggle="yes">C. rigidus</italic>, in both positive and negative ion modes, and, if available, annotation of the spectral features. Metadata can be found in the header section of the reference metabolome file (.msr or .mgf format). Like its reference genome, the reference metabolome of <italic toggle="yes">C. rigidus</italic> provides an essential reference for studies of its metabolism and physiology.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC3-2">
      <title>RefMetaPlant: a reference metabolome database and related toolset for plant metabolic research</title>
      <p>Based on the reference metabolome constructed for plants of the five major phyla, we have developed and released the first version of a reference metabolome database for plants, RefMetaPlant. We use RefMeta for its abbreviation, to parallel with ‘RefSeq’, the reference sequence database at NCBI (<xref rid="B23" ref-type="bibr">23</xref>). RefMeta contains six major components, including data resources, database documentation and statistics, and ‘Browse Metabolome’, ‘Search metabolites’, ‘Analyze spectra’ and ‘Share data’ tools (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2A</xref>, <xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary File S1</xref>).</p>
      <fig position="float" id="F2">
        <label>Figure 2.</label>
        <caption>
          <p>Overview of RefMetaPlant and its resources. (<bold>A</bold>) Overview of RefMetaPlant. RefMetaPlant comprises six major components: ‘Browse Metabolome’, ‘Search Metabolites’, ‘Analyze Spectra’, ‘Resources’, ‘Share Data’ and ‘Document &amp; Statistics’. (<bold>B</bold>) Data resources and their related workflow for RefMetaPlant. The resource data of RefMetaPlant encompass the MS data (<italic toggle="yes">n</italic> = 1 086 068) from experiments on 150+ plant species' tissues (top); a biological relevant compounds library (<italic toggle="yes">n</italic> = 383 759) (middle) and standard compounds mass spectral libraries (<italic toggle="yes">n</italic> = 325 103) (bottom).</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="gkad980fig2" position="float"/>
      </fig>
      <p>RefMetaPlant utilizes a large collection of novel and existing data, and data resources that are growing daily: (i) &gt;1 086 000 experimental mass spectra obtained in this study using UPLC coupled with Quadrupole-Orbitrap High Resolution Mass Spectrometer (UPLC-Q-Orbitrap-HRMS) on samples of &gt;150 plant species from Bryophyta, Lycopodiopsida, Pteridophyta, Gymnospermae and Angiospermae (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2B</xref>, top panel); (ii) a library of &gt;383 700 biologically relevant compounds, which includes their structural and property information that was collected from public databases like KEGG (<xref rid="B30" ref-type="bibr">30</xref>), KNApSAcK (<xref rid="B31" ref-type="bibr">31</xref>), PubChem (<xref rid="B32" ref-type="bibr">32</xref>) and UNPD (<xref rid="B33" ref-type="bibr">33</xref>) (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2B</xref> middle panel); (iii) a library of &gt;325 100 mass spectral data for standard compounds which includes 135 464 experimental reference mass spectral from public databases like MassBank (<xref rid="B8" ref-type="bibr">8</xref>), MoNA (<ext-link xlink:href="https://mona.fiehnlab.ucdavis.edu/" ext-link-type="uri">https://mona.fiehnlab.ucdavis.edu/</ext-link>), ReSpect (<xref rid="B27" ref-type="bibr">27</xref>), FiehnLib (<xref rid="B28" ref-type="bibr">28</xref>), RIKEN PlaSMA (<ext-link xlink:href="http://plasma.riken.jp/" ext-link-type="uri">http://plasma.riken.jp/</ext-link>) and data of 189 639 <italic toggle="yes">in silico</italic> mass spectra (<xref rid="B29" ref-type="bibr">29</xref>) (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2B</xref>, bottom panel); (iv) the reference metabolome (in .msr and .mgf formats) that we constructed for each of the 153 plant species (<xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary Table S4</xref>). These data are available for download and for analysis applications using our online tools.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC3-3">
      <title>Analytical functions implemented in RefMetaPlant</title>
      <p>The function ‘Browse Metabolome’ allows users to browse the reference metabolome of selected plant species and further drill into the details of each metabolite, including its formula, classification, 2D/3D structure, exact mass, SMILES, spectra and related metadata, etc. (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3A</xref>). The sample and analytical method information of each plant species can also be found from ‘metadata’ link in the ‘species metabolite’ page. In addition, the reference metabolome of selected plant species can be downloaded in files (two different formats: .msr or .mgf format) via the function ‘Share data’.</p>
      <fig position="float" id="F3">
        <label>Figure 3.</label>
        <caption>
          <p>Implementation of analytical functions in RefMetaPlant. (<bold>A</bold>) Overview of function ‘Browse Metabolome’. The metabolome of each species contains metabolites with structural and spectral information. The reference metabolome of selected species can be downloaded in files via the function ‘Share data’ in .msr or .mgf format. (<bold>B</bold>) Overview of function ‘Search Metabolites’ enabling multiple ways to query reference metabolome. Function for querying metabolites across chemical query supporting both structure sketch, molecular weight, combined parameters. RefMetaPlant also supports the identification of unknown mass spectral data by querying LC–MS and LC–MS/MS. The query results showed the structure information and spectral information of each metabolite. (<bold>C</bold>) Overview of functions ‘Analyze Spectra’ supporting analytical tools ‘RefMetaBlast’ and ‘CompoundLibBlast’. Their workflows are described in details in Materials and methods.</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="gkad980fig3" position="float"/>
      </fig>
      <p>The function ‘Search metabolites’ supports querying the reference metabolome using five different types of queries, i.e. structure sketch, molecular weight, combined parameters, LC–MS and LC–MS/MS (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3B</xref>). For the latter two, queries can be submitted with a list of precursor ion (MS1), or a parent ion (MS1) with its fragment ions (MS2), and with other options for specified plants species, tolerance of <italic toggle="yes">m</italic>/<italic toggle="yes">z</italic>, or library for query. As a result, a list of matched metabolites is returned, which allows users to view the details of each metabolite by following a link. Importantly, all plant species that contain the metabolite in their reference metabolome are shown, revealing the ‘popularity’ of the metabolite. In addition, a filter box is also provided for the above tools for users to select data from the list of returned results by typing in a parameter, such as name, molecular weight, SMILE, classification, etc.</p>
      <p>To facilitate the use of RefMeta database for plant metabolic research, we developed two related analytical tools, RefMetaBlast and CompoundLibBlast (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3C</xref>). RefMetaBlast analyzes a sample's spectra by comparing it with a selected reference metabolome for species-specific metabolic profiling. The reference metabolome selected for comparison provides a high-confidence reference for profiling of interested samples by users. The function ‘CompoundLibBlast’ analyzes a sample's spectra with selected compound libraries for automated metabolite annotation and identification. Its function is performed based on the experimental reference mass spectral data from public databases, and the <italic toggle="yes">in silico</italic> mass spectral data we generated (<xref rid="B24" ref-type="bibr">24</xref>,<xref rid="B29" ref-type="bibr">29</xref>). These spectral analytical tools are implemented through an interactive webpage with some advanced features that were not available before in an open-source tool. Query data in mzXML, mzML or mzData format are uploaded first. Data analysis is initiated by clicking the ‘Start analysis’ button, and a hyperlink is provided for long running analysis, to allow users to retrieve the results. Both RefMetaBlast and CompoundLibBlast functions return results of matched or annotated metabolites in addition to downloadable files containing extracted MS2 spectra (MGF format), and annotation data (CSV and JSON format) (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3C</xref>).</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC3-4">
      <title>Case study 1: metabolic trends during the rice grain filling period</title>
      <p>Grain filling is the growth stage in rice when fertilized ovaries acquire carbohydrate and other nutrients to synthesize starch and convert themselves into grains (<xref rid="B45" ref-type="bibr">45</xref>,<xref rid="B46" ref-type="bibr">46</xref>). It determines the yield and quality of cereal crops (<xref rid="B47" ref-type="bibr">47</xref>). Accumulation of metabolites in filling grains involves the coordination of different metabolic and cellular processes, understanding the dynamic changes of these substances, and is of great significance in study of seed development and crop breeding (<xref rid="B48" ref-type="bibr">48</xref>).</p>
      <p>We applied RefMetaBlast to analyze the metabolic profile of <italic toggle="yes">Oryza sativa</italic> var. Yangdao #6 during the process of grain filling. Rice grains from 10, 20 and 30 days after flowering (DAF), were harvested and processed for mass spectrum experiments (Figure <xref rid="F4" ref-type="fig">4A</xref>). Raw mass spectral data were extracted with ProteoWizard (<xref rid="B49" ref-type="bibr">49</xref>) before they were assigned using the rice reference metabolome and the online tool RefMetaBlast. Consequently, 468, 469 and 511 metabolites were detected above the threshold for the 10, 20 and 30 DAF grain samples, respectively (<xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary Table S5</xref>). The numbers of different metabolites identified in the rice grains varied between different developmental stages (Figure <xref rid="F4" ref-type="fig">4B</xref>). Lipid compounds were found to be the most abundant, followed by terpenoids, and flavonoids. Their numbers were generally trended higher at later growth stages except for amino acid derivatives, alkaloids and flavonoids.</p>
      <fig position="float" id="F4">
        <label>Figure 4.</label>
        <caption>
          <p>Case study of rice and corn grains utilzing RefMetaBlast and CompoundLibBlast. (<bold>A</bold>) Grains of <italic toggle="yes">Oryza sativa</italic> var. Yangdao #6 obtained at 10, 20 and 30 days after flowering (DAF). (<bold>B</bold>) The numbers of metabolites identified with RefMetaBlast at various stages of grain filling. Chemical class for metabolites is color-coded as indicated to the right. (<bold>C</bold>) Affinity propagation (AP) clustering of metabolite groups in similar temporal changes along grain filling process of <italic toggle="yes">Oryza sativa</italic> var. Yangdao #6. Each cluster represents metabolites with similar abundance profiles. (<bold>D</bold>) Circos diagram illustrating the chemical class annotation for metabolite clusters I-IX that correspond to those in (C). Chemical class labeling: A = Alkaloids, B = Amino acid derivatives, C = Flavonoids, D = Lipids, E = Nucleotides and derivatives, F = Phenols, G = Phenylpropanoids, H = Terpenoids. (<bold>E</bold>) Grains of <italic toggle="yes">Zea mays</italic> var. B73. Corn grains were harvested in March 2021 from Sanya, Hainan, and subsequently used for mass spectral analysis. (<bold>F</bold>) Metabolite compositions for grains of <italic toggle="yes">Zea mays</italic> var. B73 identified using CompoundLibBlast. (<bold>G</bold>) Comparison of metabolites identified in B73 corn grains between our results (CompoundLibBlast) and previous five studies (<xref rid="B50" ref-type="bibr">50–54</xref>). (<bold>H</bold>) Example of compounds in <italic toggle="yes">Zea mays</italic> var. B73 newly identified by CompoundLibBlast but not in previous study (<xref rid="B54" ref-type="bibr">54</xref>).</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="gkad980fig4" position="float"/>
      </fig>
      <p>For the grain metabolites assigned by RefMetaBlast, their relative abundance was grouped with affinity propagation (AP) clustering to investigate their changes in their patterns. The changes of metabolite abundance were grouped into nine distinct clusters (Figure <xref rid="F4" ref-type="fig">4C</xref>, <xref rid="F4" ref-type="fig">D</xref>). Notably, about 46% of amino acid derivatives belonged to cluster II, which showed a trend of gradual reduction between 10 DAF and 30 DAF. A substantial number of terpenoids first increased between 10 DAF and 20 DAF, then decreased between 20 DAF and 30 DAF (cluster III, cluster VI and cluster VII; Figure <xref rid="F4" ref-type="fig">4C</xref>, <xref rid="F4" ref-type="fig">D</xref>). Lipids appeared to exhibit temporal specificity, with different types of lipids present at different time points. We observed a significant proportion of lipids in Clusters II (∼25%), which was high at 10 DAF, III (∼17%), which was high at 20 DAF, and VIII (∼21%), which was high at 30 DAF. About 15% of the flavonoids were found to increase from 10 DAF to 30 DAF (clusters VIII and XI). Notably, rhoifolin and apigenin 4′-glucuronide, two derivatives of apigenin that belong to flavonoid family, were found to only be present at 30 DAF. As they share a chemical structure resembling that of anthocyanins, it remains to be determined if they play a role in the yellowing process in rice grains. The similar kinetics of different groups of metabolites during rice grain development may suggest common regulation mechanisms for the related pathways, which can help direct further study. The above findings demonstrate the utility of RefMetaBlast as a tool, enabling a deeper understanding of the changes and regulatory mechanisms of metabolites during the growth and development of rice.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC3-5">
      <title>Case study 2: discovery and expanded annotation of metabolites in maize samples</title>
      <p>The CompoundLibBlast tool was designed to annotate plant metabolites using expanded compound mass spectral libraries, including both experimental and <italic toggle="yes">in silico</italic> mass spectral data (<xref rid="B24" ref-type="bibr">24</xref>,<xref rid="B29" ref-type="bibr">29</xref>). To demonstrate its performance, we conducted an analysis of non-targeted metabolomic data for corn samples of <italic toggle="yes">Zea mays</italic> var. B73 (Figure <xref rid="F4" ref-type="fig">4E</xref>), using CompoundLibBlast. We identified a total of 746 non-redundant metabolites, which belonged to eight chemical classes (Figure <xref rid="F4" ref-type="fig">4F</xref>, <xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary Table S6</xref>). Among these, the largest class of metabolites was lipids, which contained 170 compounds, highlighting the richness of lipids in corn.</p>
      <p>To evaluate the performance of CompoundLibBlast, we compared its results with those reported in recently published studies (Figure <xref rid="F4" ref-type="fig">4G</xref>). The number of metabolites annotated by our tool increased significantly compared to those of the early studies (<xref rid="B50" ref-type="bibr">50–54</xref>). We further compared our results with that of Liang and colleagues’ (<xref rid="B54" ref-type="bibr">54</xref>), which reported the most metabolites among previous studies. Our tool, CompoundLibBlast, was able to identify additional metabolites in corn, particularly some nutrition-related substances, such as vitamin K1, riboflavin, and linoleic acid, which were not found in the 2021 study (<xref rid="B54" ref-type="bibr">54</xref>) (Figure <xref rid="F4" ref-type="fig">4H</xref>). Thus, CompoundLibBlast is shown to capture a significantly broader range of metabolites, identifying many that were previously overlooked. However, further experimental validation is necessary to establish the identities of these metabolites and their functions in biological contexts. This case proved CompoundLibBlast to be a valuable tool to expand the study of diverse metabolites in crops, offering great potentials for discovery of novel metabolites and for a deeper understanding of metabolism in plants.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC3-6">
      <title>Case study 3: specialization of secondary metabolites in the evolution of legumes</title>
      <p>The evolving functions of secondary metabolites in plants has been subjected to intense study (<xref rid="B55" ref-type="bibr">55–57</xref>). Legumes belong to the family Leguminosae, which is the third-largest plant family. It has traditionally been divided into three notable subfamilies, Caesalpinioideae, Mimosoideae, and Faboideae (<xref rid="B58" ref-type="bibr">58</xref>). We have collected samples from 27 legume plants across all three subfamilies, for which a reference metabolome was constructed (Figure <xref rid="F5" ref-type="fig">5A</xref>, left panel). Their global metabolic profiles revealed variable number of metabolites for each chemical class between these legume species (Figure <xref rid="F5" ref-type="fig">5A</xref>, right panel, <xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary Table S7</xref>). Notably, while lipids and flavonoids are the largest chemical categories in legumes, the numbers of lipids and flavonoids fluctuated the most in closely related species, despite their shared family affiliation.</p>
      <fig position="float" id="F5">
        <label>Figure 5.</label>
        <caption>
          <p>Reference Metabolome revealing specialization of secondary metabolites in evolution of legumes. (<bold>A</bold>) Taxonomic relationships and the global metabolic profiles of 27 legume species. Legume subfamilies are color-coded, namely Caesalpinioideae (blue), Mimosoideae (green) and Faboideae (purple). The distribution of metabolite class for each species is depicted to the right. (<bold>B</bold>) Distribution of metabolites in the flavonoid biosynthesis pathway in three legume subfamilies. The presence of metabolites within the pathways is indicated by colored shaded fan areas. Metabolites are labeled with their respective KEGG designations. (<bold>C</bold>) C- and O-glycosylated isoflavonoids in Faboideae. Derivatives of C-glycosylated isoflavonoids can be modified by acetyl- or malonyl- groups (left panel), and derivatives of O-glycosylated isoflavonoids can be modified by acetyl-, malonyl- or apiosyl- groups (right panel).</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="gkad980fig5" position="float"/>
      </fig>
      <p>We then took a closer look at flavonoid biosynthesis in the legume subfamilies. In the flavonoid biosynthesis pathway, the C6–C3–C6 carbon skeleton is formed (in 4-coumaroyl-CoA) from phenylalanine (Figure <xref rid="F5" ref-type="fig">5B</xref>). Then the basic flavonoid skeleton is modified by different groups of enzymes, leading to different biosynthesis pathways, and the production of many important intermediates (<xref rid="B59" ref-type="bibr">59–61</xref>). Isoflavonoids can be synthesized through two different pathway branches (Figure <xref rid="F5" ref-type="fig">5B</xref>, the yellow and blue branch). Strikingly, we found major differences in isoflavonoid biosynthesis between the three subfamilies, Caesalpinioideae, Mimosoideae, and Faboideae. Based on all the species we collected and examined, the isoflavonoid biosynthesis pathways (Figure <xref rid="F5" ref-type="fig">5B</xref>, the yellow and blue branch) were found to exist uniquely in species belonging to Faboideae. Our findings add further evidence to the restricted occurrence of isoflavonoids in the subfamily Faboideae, which is suggested to be a remarkable feature of the chemistry of the Leguminosae (<xref rid="B62" ref-type="bibr">62</xref>). The phenomena of specialized metabolites restricted to subfamilies, tribes and genera, is emphasized in a term called chemotaxonomy, for which chemical profiles were used as a systemic framework to reflect phylogeny (<xref rid="B63" ref-type="bibr">63</xref>). Our results revealed that metabolic profiles varied across the sampled legume species, with isoflavones having a restricted distribution compared to flavones and anthocyanins, which were more broadly distributed. Isoflavonoids serve numerous important physiological functions, including as anti-oxidants and phytoalexins (<xref rid="B64" ref-type="bibr">64</xref>,<xref rid="B65" ref-type="bibr">65</xref>). The data suggest that flavonoids, particularly isoflavonoids, have been strongly influenced by selection and adaptation during plant evolution.</p>
      <p>We further examined ∼400 isoflavonoids that are specifically present in Faboideae. These metabolites were C-glycosylated and O-glycosylated isoflavonoids, which can be further modified by acetyl-, malonyl- and apiosyl- groups. For example, the C-glycosylated isoflavonoid puerarin can be modified by acetyl-, and malonyl- groups, leading to production of puerarin 6′'-acetate and puerarin 6′'-O-malonate, respectively (Figure <xref rid="F5" ref-type="fig">5C</xref>, left panel). On the other hand, formononetin can be modified by a glucoside, and subsequently by acetyl-, malonyl- or apiosyl- groups to form different isoflavone derivatives (Figure <xref rid="F5" ref-type="fig">5C</xref>, right panel). Our findings added new members to the list of O-glycosylated isoflavonoids with malonyl-modifications reported for legume species (<xref rid="B63" ref-type="bibr">63</xref>). For plant natural products, glycosylation is a versatile modification used to enhance their solubility and stability, and promote storage in plant cells (<xref rid="B66" ref-type="bibr">66</xref>). It also affects bioactivity and bioavailability of natural products (<xref rid="B67" ref-type="bibr">67</xref>). Taken together, these findings provide valuable insights into the ecological adaptation and evolution of legumes.</p>
    </sec>
  </sec>
  <sec id="SEC4">
    <title>Summary and future directions</title>
    <p>In recent decades, study in the field of plant metabolism has advanced rapidly, largely driven by metabolomics research, and has revealed an astounding amount of chemical diversity in this ancient kingdom. For a given species, the metabolome and metabolites of a species is analogous the genome and genes, and in the latter case, a reference genome provides a valuable foundational resource. However, the lack of a reference metabolome for plants, and deficits of high-quality standard compound spectral libraries and high-throughput analytical tools, have hindered the discovery and functional study of phytochemicals. The ideal reference metabolome for a plant species consists of mass spectral data (MS1/MS2) for all its metabolites across all organs/tissues of the species. With this goal in mind, we have undertaken efforts to address the specific challenges in plant metabolomics research. First, by leveraging the most advanced LC–MS platform, we generated untargeted mass spectral data over a period of five years, from &gt;150 plant species across the five major phyla of green plants. Second, we built RefMetaPlant, a ‘Reference Metabolome Database for Plants’. Using a computation protocol that we developed for constructing reference metabolomes, the first release of RefMetaPlant contains reference metabolomes for 153 plant species. Third, RefMetaPlant has designated functions for metabolic research that were aimed to parallel that of RefSeq for genomic studies. In the RefMetaPlant platform, we have integrated standard compound mass spectral libraries to assist annotation, including both experimental reference mass spectra and <italic toggle="yes">in silico</italic> mass spectra. We have also developed a set of related query and analytical tools like ‘LC–MS/MS Query’, ‘RefMetaBlast’ and ‘CompoundLibBlast’ for plant metabolome searches and profiling, and metabolite identification. Thus, RefMetaPlant provides a powerful platform to support plant metabolome research and genome-scale metabolomics analysis, whose utility for metabolic research mirrors that of RefSeq for genomic studies.</p>
    <p>Like a reference genome, a reference metabolome would ideally incorporate continuous updates when more and better-quality data become available in association with the advancement of metabolomics technologies. As the field of plant metabolomics rapidly evolves, updates and expansion of RefMetaPlant will be crucial to keep pace with developments in the field. RefMetaPlant aims to become a centralized platform for plant metabolomic research. Its continuous expansion to include more organisms and metabolites is critically important to ensure its relevance, and to facilitate cross-referencing of information across studies.</p>
    <p>RefMetaPlant database also serves as a collaborative platform, promoting knowledge/data sharing utilities and cross-field collaborative research. Besides housing reference metabolomes for &gt;150 plants species that are available for online analysis and download, a data submission utility is provided for cross-team collaborations and for updating existing reference metabolomes or adding additional plant species. We seek to establish a secure and reliable system to facilitate big data exchange and to support the classification, collection, integration, quality control, archiving and ‘one-stop’ management, of plant metabolome data. Scientists from interdisciplinary fields can contribute their data, expanding the scope and depth of RefMetaPlant resources. Thus, RefMetaPlant will foster new collaborations in the field of metabolomic research, benefiting the research community through enhancing the distribution of collective knowledge.</p>
    <p>In conclusion, the establishment of a plant reference metabolome database represents a significant milestone in plant metabolomics research. RefMetaPlant provides an invaluable resource, contributing to a comprehensive understanding of plant metabolism across diverse plant species, empowering researchers to delve deeper into the intricacies of plant metabolism.</p>
  </sec>
